#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""Terminal review helper for branch changes.

review compares the current branch against a base ref, shows changed files in a
full-screen curses UI, and stores per-file reviewed checkboxes under
.git/review/<base>...<branch>/state.json. The default UI keeps a side-by-side
diff at the top, a compact comment summary below it, and the changed-file list at
the bottom.

Local review comments are written directly into changed files with markers such
as "#review this is hard to read". Publishing scans those markers, creates
GitLab/GitHub MR or PR comments, remembers already published marker IDs, and
removes successfully published standalone marker lines from the working tree.
Inline markers are left untouched.

Remote discussions are auto-loaded when the UI starts and can be refreshed with
R. The comments popup groups remote notes into threads, highlights replies, and
allows replying to a selected remote comment from inside the tool.

Useful keys in the UI:
- / starts regex file search.
- Space toggles the reviewed checkbox for the selected file.
- f cycles all/unchecked/checked filters.
- n/N jumps to the next or previous unreviewed file.
- c/e opens the selected file in the configured editor.
- d opens the selected diff in the pager.
- m opens the threaded comments popup; Up/Down or j/k select comments, r replies.
- o opens the current GitLab MR or GitHub PR in the browser.
- p publishes local #review markers, with output shown in a popup.

Editor selection for c/e and the edit subcommand follows normal shell defaults:
VISUAL is used first, then EDITOR, then nvim. Examples:
- VISUAL=zed review
- VISUAL="zed --wait" review
- VISUAL="code --wait" review
- EDITOR=vim review

For a lightweight picker instead of the full TUI, run "review --fast". It opens
fzf with a delta-powered preview above the file list and respects --base.
"""

